<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
In the field 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amnicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea amnicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(especially 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="amnicola" subSpecies="amnicola">
subsp. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">amnicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) is usually easily recognised by the relatively small corolla which is pale pink with a dark centre. It often blankets shrubs and small trees where it occurs. The leaves are quite glabrous, usually somewhat glaucous and slightly fleshy. It is not a very easy plant to dry successfully so leaves are often deciduous on herbarium specimens. It can be confused rather easily with species from the 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Liliopsida" family="Eriospermaceae" genus="Batatas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Batatas</taxonomicName>
Clade.
</paragraph>
